The integral will become less complicated if we make a substitution
$\displaystyle u = \ln(x)$.

\subparagraph{First substitution}\label{first-substitution}

If $\displaystyle u = \ln(x)$ then $du = (1/x)\,dx$. We would like to
express $\displaystyle dx$ in terms of $\displaystyle u$ and
$\displaystyle du$. Isolating $\displaystyle dx$ gives
$\displaystyle dx = x\,du$. Solving for $\displaystyle x$ in
$\displaystyle u = \ln(x)$ gives $\displaystyle x = e^{u}$ and hence
$\displaystyle dx = e^u\,du$. Therefore,

\begin{align*}
I = \int \sin(\ln(x))\,dx = \int e^u \sin(u)\,du
\end{align*}

\subparagraph{First integration by
parts}\label{first-integration-by-parts}

To find this integral, we will need to integrate by parts twice.

Let $\displaystyle f = e^u$ and $dg = \sin(u)\,du$. Then $df = e^u\,du$
and $\displaystyle g = -\cos(u)$. Thus,

\begin{align*}
I &= \int f\,dg \\
&= fg - \int g\,df \\
&= e^u (-\cos(u)) - \int  -\cos(u)e^u\,du \\
&= -e^u \cos(u) + \int e^u \cos(u)\,du
\end{align*}

\subparagraph{Second integration by
parts}\label{second-integration-by-parts}

We repeat the process on the second integral. This time, we let
$\displaystyle v = e^u$ and $dw = \cos(u)\,du$. Thus,
$\displaystyle dv = e^u du$ and $\displaystyle w = \sin(u)$. Now we
find:

\begin{align*}
I &= -e^u \cos(u) + \int v\,dw \\
&= -e^u \cos(u) + vw - \int w\,dv \\
&= -e^u \cos(u) + e^u \sin(u) - \int \sin(u)e^u\,du
\end{align*}

\subparagraph{Inspect the result}\label{inspect-the-result}

We recognize the integral above as $\displaystyle I$ and we can now
solve for $\displaystyle I$:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
I = -e^u \cos(u) + e^u \sin(u) - I
\end{align*} so

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
2I = -e^u \cos(u) + e^u \sin(u)
\end{align*}

Then

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
I = \frac{1}{2} e^u (\sin(u) - \cos(u)) + C
\end{align*}

We added the arbitrary constant $\displaystyle C$ because we are
computing an indefinite integral.

\subparagraph{Bring \emph{x} back}\label{bring-x-back}

Finally, the integral we desire can be found by replacing
$\displaystyle u$ by $\displaystyle \ln(x)$ so that
$\displaystyle e^u = x$ :

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
I = \frac{1}{2} x (\sin (\ln(x)) - \cos (\ln (x))) + C
\end{align*}
